INSTRUCTIONS

Overview

Building complex apps can be a daunting task. Such apps typically involve advanced planning, data manipulation/restructuring, defining functions and sub-routines, computing/resource allocation decisions, and the process is almost never linear in nature. One should always try to think several steps ahead or even plan for future adjustments (i.e.Â efficient coding). Obviously, building complex shiny apps requires a deep understanding of how to construct plots/graphics in R. Fortunately, we spent the first part of the course developing a deep understanding of ggplot2.

The goal of this lab is to leverage this knowledge to reinforce and extend the shiny techniques we have learned.

Dataset

For Exercise 1 you will need to unzip/decompress the provided data.zip file and then place the unzipped/decompressed data folder into the app directory. This folder contains the .shp file (shape files) with the state/county geometries and other variables needed for the app.

Exercises

Exercise 1

Recreate the app pictured in FigureÂ 1 below. It has two widgets, one for state and one for the variable.

Hint: Lesson 5 may have helpful parts on creating widgets, if you get stuck.

  1. read in data/county_data.shp using the sf::read_sf()

  2. create a widget to select the state - may be helpful to extract a vector of unique state names from the dataset

  3. create a widget for variable with 4 options: "Percent White", "Percent Black", "Percent Hispanic", "Percent Asian"

  4. note the colors you will use are "darkgreen", "black","darkorange", and "darkviolet", respectively.

  5. in the server define:

    • a new dataset that is subset by state (pick any state for now, maybe "Illinois", we will use the widget later)
    • a variable assigning the variable to display from your dataset (ie: var <- "white")
    • a variable for the color. (ie: color <- "darkgreen")

    Helpful tip: It is easier to define placeholder variables in the server that will change based on widget selection. But donât link these to your widgets just yet! Letâs get a working plot first! This way we will be able to run the ggplot code and debug in your file rather than having to run the app every time to see our plot.

  6. After you define these 3 objects, use ggplot to make your plot. The plot should use your new dataset, var, and color defined above.

    Helpful tip: This is useful because if done correctly when you link the widgets you will not have to make any adjustments to your working plot. All changes will occur in the variables defined before the plot.

  7. Now link each widget one at a time to the variables you defined in the server, making sure everything runs correctly after each one to help with debugging.

Exercise 2

Set up a free shiny.io account to share an app. Lesson 7 covers many methods to share your apps and your choice depends on the intended use of your app. Consider sharing shiny apps on your resume, cv, personal and/or professional website.

  1. Begin by going to http://www.shinyapps.io/. click sign up. and follow the instructions to set up a free account.

  2. Continue to follow the instructions to upload one of your apps (ANY app you want) to your new account.

  3. After uploading your app ensure that it is working and then submit the url/link to the L12 shiny 3: url/link assignment on Canvas.

Important

Your submission for this lab is in 2 parts:

  1. A zip folder with at least one app in it (Exercise 1), might have challenge apps in it, submitted to L12 shiny 3 Canvas assignment.
  2. A url/link submitted to the L12 shiny 3: url/link Canvas assignment.

The Canvas gradebook will be configured to handle these as one 20 point lab.
